      <bioghist id="aspace_4aa625b98c26c07b17bd4dfe8066a4e1">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>The Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee (SNCC) was a civil rights organization and served as the youth and autonomously run branch of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference. It was founded with the support of Ella Baker in April 1960 at Shaw University in Raleigh, NC. SNCC was focused on racial de-segregation and voting rights for the Black community in the American South. SNCC was active between 1960-1970, with the height of their political activity between the early to mid-1960's. This included the Mississippi Freedom Summer project of 1964, co-organized by the Congress on Racial Equality (CORE), the Council of Federated Organizations (COFO), and SNCC. Approximately 1,000 (or more) white college students, from the American North, volunteered to organize and teach in approximately 40 Freedom Schools across the American South. The Freedom Schools focused on voter registration, the establishment of a new political party, history, and other subjects Freedom School students were interested in.</p>
         <p>Karen Haberman Trusty (born 1945) atteded Spelman College, a Historcially Black College and University (HBCU), in the Fall of 1963 through the National Student Association Spelman Exchange Program. She was one of very few white students to particiapte in the program. At Spelman, Haberman Trusty was recruited by James Forman into the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee (SNCC). Haberman Trusty was active with SNCC between 1963-1964 participating in many sit-in demonstrations, non-violent protests, Mississippi Freedom Summer, and other organizing activities.  She was arrested three times, including a Fourth of July arrest in 1964. Her and three Black SNCC organizers, including Matthew Jones, a civil rights and Southern Freedom Movement singer, were beaten and arrested after non-violently protesting at a Ku Klux Klan (KKK) rally at Stone Mountain in Atlanta, GA by rally participants. She served as support staff for the Mississippi Freedom Summer project in 1964 at the SNCC Atlanta, GA and Greenwood, MS offices. During that summer, she worked on the Wide Area Telephone Service (WATS) line in Greenwood where she co-collected reports of racially motivated hate-crimes. After organizing with SNCC and returning to Connecticut, she transferred and completed her BA at Harvard University's Department of Social Relations. She went on to organize poor white communities in Detroit, MI and across Appalachia. In 2010, she co-created with then Portland State University student, Conci Althouse, the documentary <title render="italic">
               <part>In Rarefied Air</part>
            </title> on her organizing experiences with SNCC and the legacy of racism in the U.S.</p>
         <p>"Exchange: Three White Women Students at Spelman, 1962-1964, A Discussion," Veterans of the Civil Rights Movement, Civil Rights Movement Archive Inc., accessed March 7, 2024. https://www.crmvet.org/disc/spelman.htm.</p>
         <p>"About Karen," In Rarefied Air, accessed March 7, 2024. https://www.inrarefiedair.com/about-karen.html.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_f00e8211b973c981936061392dd42ab5">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The collection chronicles Habermann Trusty's involvement in the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee (SNCC) between 1963-1964 and commemorative SNCC and civil rights-based events between 1980's-2010's. The collection contains administrative files, periodicals and clippings, ephemera, and audiovisual material. The collection contains materials related to other SNCC organizers and civil rights activists. Such as Dr. Endesha Mae "Cat" Holland, Dorothy Height, Matthew Jones, Dr. Bernice Johnson Reagon, Mardon Walker, Betty Garman, and Dr. Robert Coles.</p>
         <p>Racist, anti-Black language is present throughout the collection. Including images and descriptions of carceral violence, police violence, sexual harassment by police, and physical beatings and assault. The Wide Area Telephone (WATS) Line reports folder contains descriptions of racially motivated hate crimes, police harassment/violence, Ku Klux Klan (KKK) intimidation, church bombings, death threats, beatings, false allegations of sexual assault and rape, unlawful arrests/detainment, and disappearances of SNCC fieldworkers.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      <arrangement id="aspace_96bc000144a73907ade747c9dc691620">
         <head>Arrangement</head>
         <p>Materials are organized into five groupings; Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee (SNCC) Mississippi Freedom Summer project (1964-2014), Dr. Endesha Ida Mae Holland, <title render="italic">
               <part>From the Mississippi Delta</part>
            </title> related materials (1995), Dr. Bernice Johnson Reagon related materials (1997, undated), Printed ephemera and newspaper clippings (1978-1981), and <title render="italic">
               <part>Spirit of Freedom</part>
            </title> CD (2019). Within these groups, materials are further grouped by function and arranged chronologically therein.</p>
      </arrangement>
